		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Alg=
orithm for finding a zero of a function</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about searching for zeros of continuous functions. For searching a fini=
te sorted array, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_search=
_algorithm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binary search algorithm">binary =
search algorithm</a>. For the method of determining what software change ca=
used a change in behavior, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bis=
ection_(software_engineering)" title=3D"Bisection (software engineering)">B=
isection (software engineering)</a>.</div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Bisection_method.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https:/=
/upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Bisection_method.svg/250=
px-Bisection_method.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"291=
" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"838" data-file-height=3D"977=
"></a><figcaption>A few steps of the bisection method applied over the star=
ting range [a<sub>1</sub>;b<sub>1</sub>]. The bigger red dot is the root of=
 the function.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>bisection method</b> is a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root-finding_algorithm" title=3D"Root-finding algori=
thm">root-finding method</a> that applies to any <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">continuou=
s function</a> for which one knows two values with opposite signs. The meth=
od consists of repeatedly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisectio=
n" title=3D"Bisection">bisecting</a> the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)" title=3D"Interval (mathematics)">interval</a=
> defined by these values, then selecting the  subinterval in which the fun=
ction changes sign, which therefore must contain a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Root_of_a_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Root of=
 a function">root</a>. It is a very simple and robust method, but it is als=
o relatively slow. Because of this, it is often used to obtain a rough appr=
oximation to a solution which is then used as a starting point for more rap=
idly converging methods.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_method#cite_note-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
The method is also called the <b>interval halving</b> method,<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisec=
tion_method#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Binary_search_algorithm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binary se=
arch algorithm">binary search method</a></b>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_method#ci=
te_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> or the <b>dichotomy method</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_met=
hod#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Po=
lynomial">polynomials</a>, more elaborate methods exist for testing the exi=
stence of a root in an interval (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
escartes%27_rule_of_signs" title=3D"Descartes' rule of signs">Descartes' ru=
le of signs</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sturm%27s_theorem=
" title=3D"Sturm's theorem">Sturm's theorem</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Budan%27s_theorem" title=3D"Budan's theorem">Budan's theorem=
</a>). They allow extending the bisection method into efficient algorithms =
for finding all real roots of a polynomial; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Real-root_isolation" title=3D"Real-root isolation">Real-root =
isolation</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"The_method">The method</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBisection_method=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: The method"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>The method is applicable for numerically solving the equation <span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-math=
ml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"htt=
p://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle f(x)=3D0}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
