<p>The bisection method has been generalized to multi-dimensional functions=
. Such methods are called <b>generalized bisection methods</b>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bi=
section_method#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_method#cite_not=
e-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> =20
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Methods_based_on_degree_com=
putation">Methods based on degree computation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBisection_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;se=
ction=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Methods based on degree computation"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>Some of these methods are based on computing the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Topological_degree" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Topolo=
gical degree">topological degree</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_method#cite_note-1=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Characteristic_bisection_me=
thod">Characteristic bisection method</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DBisection_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
7" title=3D"Edit section: Characteristic bisection method"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <b>characteristic bisection method</b> uses only the signs of a func=
tion in different points. Lef <i>f</i> be a function from R<sup><i>d</i></s=
up> to R<sup><i>d</i></sup>, for some integer <i>d</i> =E2=89=A5 2. A <b>ch=
aracteristic polyhedron</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_method#cite_note-13"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> (also called an <b>admissible polygon</b>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_14-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_met=
hod#cite_note-:2-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> of <i>f</i> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedron" title=3D"Polyhedron">polyhedron</a> in R<sup><i=
>d</i></sup>, having 2<sup>d</sup> vertices, such that in each vertex <b>v<=
/b>, the combination of signs of <i>f</i>(<b>v</b>) is unique. For example,=
 for <i>d</i>=3D2, a characteristic polyhedron of <i>f</i> is a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" title=3D"Quadrilateral">quadri=
lateral</a> with vertices (say) A,B,C,D, such that:
</p>
<ul><li>Sign <i>f</i>(A) =3D (=E2=88=92,=E2=88=92), that is, <i>f</i><sub>1=
</sub>(A)&lt;0, <i>f</i><sub>2</sub>(A)&lt;0.</li>
<li>Sign <i>f</i>(B) =3D (=E2=88=92,+),  that is, <i>f</i><sub>1</sub>(B)&l=
t;0, <i>f</i><sub>2</sub>(B)&gt;0.</li>
<li>Sign <i>f</i>(C) =3D (+,=E2=88=92),  that is, <i>f</i><sub>1</sub>(C)&g=
t;0, <i>f</i><sub>2</sub>(C)&lt;0.</li>
<li>Sign <i>f</i>(D) =3D (+,+),  that is, <i>f</i><sub>1</sub>(D)&gt;0, <i>=
f</i><sub>2</sub>(D)&gt;0.</li></ul>
<p>A <b>proper edge</b> of a characteristic polygon is a edge between a pai=
r of vertices, such that the sign vector differs by only a single sign. In =
the above example, the proper edges of the characteristic quadrilateral are=
 AB, AC, BD and CD. A <b>diagonal</b> is a pair of vertices, such that the =
sign vector differs by all <i>d</i> signs. In the above example, the diagon=
als are AD and BC.
</p><p>At each iteration, the algorithm picks a proper edge of the polyhedr=
on (say, A--B), and computes the signs of <i>f</i> in its mid-point (say, M=
). Then it proceeds as follows:
</p>
<ul><li>If Sign <i>f</i>(M) =3D Sign(A), then A is replaced by M, and we ge=
t a smaller characteristic polyhedron.</li>
<li>If Sign <i>f</i>(M) =3D Sign(B), then B is replaced by M, and we get a =
smaller characteristic polyhedron.</li>
<li>Else, we pick a new proper edge and try again.</li></ul>
<p>Suppose the diameter (=3D length of longest proper edge) of the original=
 characteristic polyhedron is <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">D</span>. Then, at least <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-m=
ath-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a=
11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Ma=
thML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \log _{2}(D/\varepsilon )}">
